  "prompt": "What is Goldman Sachs discretionary compensation structure (preferably by division)?",
  "response": "Goldman Sachs, like many investment banks, has a discretionary compensation structure that typically includes base salary and a variable bonus component, which can be influenced by individual performance, team performance, and overall bank performance. The specifics of their compensation structure can vary by division and may not be publicly disclosed in detail. However, here\u2019s a general overview of how compensation is typically structured across different divisions:\n\n1. **Investment Banking Division (IBD)**: \n   - Analysts and Associates typically have a significant portion of their compensation as performance bonuses, which can be tied to deal flow and personal contributions to the team\u2019s success. Higher-level roles (VPs, Directors, Managing Directors) have increasing bonuses that reflect their seniority and contributions to major projects.\n\n2. **Global Markets**: \n   - For sales and trading roles, bonuses are heavily performance-based and can be substantial, especially in years of strong trading performance. Compensation is often linked directly to personal revenue generation, as traders and salespeople are evaluated based on their ability to drive profit.\n\n3. **Asset Management**: \n   - In this division, compensation can be tied to client performance and the overall success of funds. Bonuses can also be linked to the growth and retention of client assets.\n\n4. **Consumer & Wealth Management**: \n   - Compensation here may include incentives based on client satisfaction and retention, alongside traditional performance measures. Wealth advisors may receive bonuses based on the assets they manage and the profitability of their client relationships.\n\n5. **Investment Research**: \n   - Analysts and researchers typically have a mix of salary and bonuses, with bonuses reflecting the success and accuracy of their research as well as the overall performance of the firm.\n\n6. **Technology & Operations**: \n   - Compensation in these areas may be more structured with a blend of competitive salaries and performance bonuses. However, it is generally lower than in front-office roles (IBD and Global Markets).\n\nOverall, while base salaries provide a steady income, bonuses can vary significantly based on individual performance, division performance, and overall firm profitability. Compensation structures are subject to change and vary by year and economic conditions. For the most accurate and detailed information, consulting transparency reports from Goldman Sachs or financial news sources that cover compensation trends in banking would be beneficial.",
